         <head>NOTES <hi rend="small">to the</hi> POEM <hi rend="small">of </hi>
                              MICHAEL.</head>
         <div xml:id="note1m">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">NOTE I. </hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note"> Page 224—line 6. “There’s Richard
                                   Bateman,” &amp;c. The <lb/>story alluded to here is well
                                   known in the country. The cha-<lb/>pel is called Ings Chapel ;
                                   and is on the right hand side of <lb/>the road leading from
                                   Kendal to Ambleside.</p>
         </div>
         <div xml:id="note2m">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">NOTE II. </hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note"> Page 227—line 15.
                                   “———had design’d to build a
                                   sheep-<lb/>fold,” &amp;c. It may be proper to inform some
                                   readers, that a <lb/>sheep-fold in these mountains is an unroofed
                                   building of <lb/>stone walls, with different divisions. It is
                                   generally placed <lb/>by the side of a brook, for the convenience
                                   of washing the <lb/>sheep; but it is also useful as a shelter for
                                   them, and as a <lb/>place to drive them into, to enable the
                                   shepherds conveni-<lb/>ently to single out one or more for any
                                   particular purpose.</p>
         </div>
         <lb/>
         <lb/>
         <trailer>
            <hi rend="small">END.</hi>
            <lb/>
